Projecting 2015 Fantasy Points - Hitter¶

There are numerous performance projection models out there. Here I present a simple model that is more for exploratory purposes rather than accuracy. Everything except the statistical model section and the code section is meant for a general audience where the only requisite is to be able to read a scatter plot. I do present a more detailed statistical model for those interested and also present parameter estimates, confidence intervals, p-values and ANOVA results.

Each section will be labeled (t) for "technical" and (n) for "non-technical". Anything labeled (t) is not required to understand the gist of the results. Also, to hide the code used to generate the results, click the "toggle input" button at the top of the page to hide all code.

Summary (n)¶

The goal is to be able to efficiently forecast a hitter's fantasy performance in 2015 given all information available. Of course, there is a lot of information about a player (for example, his 60-yd dash time or maximum dead lift amount), but we need to be selective about the information we choose.

The most obvious way to "guess" how a player will do in 2015 is to look at how he has been doing (e.g. stats for 2014). Of course, even this assumption is questionable since some player's performance varies wildly from year to year ( or week to week if you're Jay Bruce). That said, we will see that there are indeed some correlations across time. That is, if a player did "well" in 2014, then it is reasonable to expect we will do well in 2015.

So what do we choose as the variables of interest? For this initial experiment, we will use:

  • 2014 BA
  • 2014 Home runs (HR) per at bat (AB)
  • 2014 doubles (2B) per AB
  • 2014 Stolen Bases (SB) - Caught Stealing (CS)
  • 2014 walks (BB) per AB
  • 2014 RBI per AB
  • 2014 Runs per AB
  • 3 year avg HR per AB
  • 3 year average BA
  • 3 year avg 2B per AB
  • Career Strike outs per AB
  • Age

We will call these stats "explanatory variables". For the most part, the explanatory variables seem like a reasonable set of criteria to make our forecast. However, there are a couple aspects that deserve a more detailed explanation.

Career and 2014 stats¶

The reason for including both 2014 and career stats is to capture the effect of both career trends and recent averages. Intuitively, when forecasting an obvious question is whether the player's most current performance is characteristic of his career or if the recent performance is an anomaly. For example, Altuve never hit higher than .290 until last year when he hit .341. We might wonder which piece of information is more important. Is his breakout year indicative of a promising career or will he return as a career sub-300 hitter?

Statistical Model, data and code (t)¶

The model is a simple linear regression with the variables listed above as the exogenous cofactors and total fantasy points per game as the dependent variable. Since this model is so simple, I am not going to consider heteroskedasticity or multi-collinearity issues (yet). If data is not available for a player for 3 years, the 3 year average variable will be the average of the number of years available (this is also another possibility of improvement). For players, I use any player in 2014 that had at least 100 ABs.

The Code¶

This is not the complete code. Most of the heavy lifting is done by the proscout software I have been working on. This is just an illustration of how to use the software.

def get_standard_batting(url=r'http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/2014-standard-batting.shtml', 
                         at_bats=100):
    """
    Gets the 2014 standard batting line for all MLB players
    with ABs>at_bats.  Also adds a column for total fantasy
    points TFP.
    
    url :
        standard batting table from baseball reference
    """
    page = urllib2.urlopen(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(page.read())
    tables = soup.findAll('table')
    players_batting = tables[1]
    df = pd.read_html(players_batting.prettify())[0]
    df = df.drop(df.columns[-1],1).convert_objects(
        convert_numeric=True).dropna()
    cols = [col.split('\n')[1].split(' ')[-1] for col in df.columns]
    df.columns = cols
    abqual = df[df['AB']>=100]
    player_list = list(set([p.split(u'\xa0')[0] + ' ' + p.split(u'\xa0')[1].split(' ')[0] 
                            for p in abqual['Name']])) # List of players, playing with format
    return abqual, player_list

def get_variable_row(player, year=2014, pergame=True, forecast=False):
    """
    This function gets a row of the X variable for a player.
    To get the full covariate matrix, we need to loop through players.
    
    Year is the year of the dependent variable
    """
    try :
        stats = ps.analyze_tools.Player(player).get_season_stats()
    except :
        print player + ' page is non-standard '
        return None
    try:
        ref_year = stats.ix[year]
    except:
        ref_year = stats.ix[year - 1] # Hack for getting projection data
    if not forecast:
        # If we are forecasting, we do not enter here because
        # we are trying to forecast TFP
        tfp = ref_year['1B'] + 2*ref_year['2B'] + 3*ref_year['3B'] + 4*ref_year['HR'] + \
            ref_year['BB'] + ref_year['R'] + ref_year['RBI'] - ref_year['SO']+ref_year['SH'] + \
            ref_year['SF'] + 2*ref_year['SB'] + ref_year['HBP'] - ref_year['CS']-ref_year['GDP']
        tfp = tfp/ref_year['G']
    covariates = []
    ## Let's just go through and add to the list
    ## Might want to make this a separate function
    prev_year= year - 1
    try:
        last_year = stats.ix[int(prev_year)]
    except KeyError:
        print 'Data for ' + player + ' not available in ' + str(prev_year)
        return None
    age = ref_year['Age']
    # Last year data
    covariates.append(last_year['HR']/(last_year['AB'])) # Homers
    covariates.append(last_year['BA'])
    covariates.append(last_year['SB']-last_year['CS'])
    covariates.append(last_year['BB']/float(last_year['AB']))
    covariates.append(last_year['RBI'] / last_year['AB'])
    covariates.append(last_year['R'] / last_year['AB'])
    covariates.append(last_year['2B'] / last_year['AB'])
    # Career strikeout rate
    covariates.append(sum(stats['SO'])/sum(stats['AB']))
    # Age
    try:
        prev_3 = stats[np.bool_((np.int_(stats.index>=year-3) * np.int_(stats.index<=year-1)))]
    # 3 year HR and BA
        covariates.append(sum(prev_3['HR']) / sum(prev_3['AB']))
        covariates.append(sum(prev_3['H']) / sum(prev_3['AB']))
        covariates.append(sum(prev_3['2B']) / sum(prev_3['AB']))
        
        #covariates.append(age * last_year['HR']/(last_year['AB']))
        #covariates.append(last_year['BA']*age)
        #covariates.append(age * last_year['BB']/float(last_year['AB']))
        #covariates.append(age * last_year['RBI'] / last_year['AB'])
        #covariates.append(age * last_year['R'] / last_year['AB'])
        #covariates.append(age * last_year['2B'] / last_year['AB'])
    except:
        covariates.append(last_year['HR']/(last_year['AB']))
        covariates.append(last_year['BA'])
        covariates.append(last_year['2B'] / last_year['AB'])
    covariates.append(age)
    covariates.append(age**2)
    if not forecast:
        return tfp, covariates
    else:
        return covariates

Results (n)¶

First, let us look at some scatter plots. In the plots below, we see how each of the variables are correlated with each other. The plots along the "diagonal" (i.e. the plots beginning in the top left cell and going diagonal toward the bottom left) are the histogram of the variable. That is, the top right plot is the distribution of total fantasy points per game for all of the players included in the analysis. (For example, about 60 players had about 2.0 fantasy points per game in 2014 because the 5th bar in the top left histogram extends to 60 and that corresponds to approx 2 fantasy points per game)

scatter_matrix(dfxy, figsize=(20, 20));

Commentary on the plots¶

Correlataions with TFP/Game¶

The first element to note is the almost vertical relationships between some of the variables and TFP. This will cause an issue determining which factors actually matter (statistical significance) because we do not have sufficient variation in the explanatory variables. Nevertheless, some variables such as batting average, career strikeouts and career batting average have clear linear relationships with total fantasy points.

Age¶

The plats that show the relationship between age and other variables is also interesting. First of all, it is interesting to note that the only clear relationships with age are in career strikeouts and home run categories. The negative relationship shows that older players tend to strike out less. Not surprising since many young players are impatient at the plate and their patience develops as they age. Also, this shows that players tend to hit more home runs as they get deeper into their career. This may also be a result of being more patient at the plate but there can be other factors as well.

Multicollinearity in the explanatory variables¶

Remember, we are using stats from previous years to forecast next season's fantasy points. However, some of the previous years stats are correlated. For example, player's that hit a lot of home runs also probably have a ton of RBIs. This is a problem in regression known as multicollinearity. The way to understand this is that we know that more home runs and more RBIs increase fantasy points. However, when they are so closely related, the model "cannot tell" if the increase in fantasy points is due to RBIs or home runs.

Also, we see almost a perfect linear relationship between 1 year and 3 year stats. Therefore, we will drop the 1 year stats and only use the 3 year stats for the variables we included 3. This will help bypass some multicollinearity.

In a perfect world, I would use a regression technique called generalized maximum entropy to account for this but I do not feel like coding this up right now so I will take the easy way out and just drop some variables from the final regression.

Discussion (n)¶

As expected, previous home runs, walks, strikeouts, doubles, stolen bases and batting average all help to predict future fantasy performance. Maybe surprising, age has no affect on fantasy points.

The forecast (n)¶

Here, we use the model we built to forecast the top fantasy hitters in 2015. The list starts below the last snippet of code. Of course, I would not consider the data "cleaned" so some of the projections may be skewed by factors that I did not control for (injuries, trades, ballapark). However, the rankings seem pretty reasonable to me. Take it for what you want. If you have any questions, would like to discuss or have some ideas for other experiments, please let me know.

projections_pergame = []
for p in players:
    line = get_variable_row(str(p), year=2015, forecast=True)
    if (line is not None) and (len(line)==13):
        line =np.asarray(line).reshape(1,13)
        x_line = pd.DataFrame(line, columns = ["HRperAB", "BA", "SBNet","BBperAB", "RBIperAB", "RperAB", 
                                   "doublesperAB", 
                             "SOperABCareer", "HRperAB3yr", "BA3yr", "doublesperAB3yr", "Age", 
                             "Agesquared"])
        y, X = dmatrices("BA ~ HRperAB3yr  + SBNet + BBperAB  + SOperABCareer + " + 
                          "BA3yr + doublesperAB3yr + Age + Agesquared", data=x_line)
        pred = res.predict(X)
        if len(pred) != 0: #No NANS
            projections_pergame.append(float(res.predict(X)))
        else:
            projections_pergame.append(np.nan)
    else:
        projections_pergame.append(np.nan)
per_game_arr_projections = np.asarray(projections_pergame)
ranking_pergame = np.argsort(per_game_arr_projections)[::-1]
